"title":"Hypercortisolism (Cushing Syndrome)",
"jsonContent":{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_en_s13",
"title":{
"__html":"Hypercortisolism (Cushing Syndrome)"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"534885",
"children":[
"Hypercortisolism (Cushing Syndrome)"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_en_s13_1",
"title":{
"__html":"Diagnosis"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"523223",
"children":[
"Diagnosis"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"ed5ca5",
"children":[
"Cushing syndrome results from excess glucocorticoid."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"b19641",
"children":[
"The most common cause of Cushing syndrome is the use of systemic, topical, intra-articular, or inhaled glucocorticoids. Doses of prednisone (or equivalent) >10 to 20 mg/d can cause hypothalamic–pituitary–adrenal axis suppression after ≥3 weeks of consecutive use."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"1e6998",
"children":[
"Endogenous causes of Cushing syndrome can be ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"adrenocorticotropic hormone",
"children":[
"ACTH"
]
},
" dependent or independent."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"199583",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"ACTH-dependent"
]
},
" causes of Cushing syndrome are defined by ACTH levels elevated or inappropriately “normal” in relation to the cortisol level:"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"d6f8f9",
"children":[
"ACTH-secreting pituitary adenomas (Cushing disease)"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"8f43b7",
"children":[
"ACTH-secreting carcinomas and carcinoid tumors"
]
},
" "
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"5fb334",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"ACTH-independent"
]
},
" causes of Cushing syndrome are defined by low or “normal” ACTH levels in relation to the cortisol level:"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"88099e",
"children":[
"adrenal adenomas"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"73997f",
"children":[
"adrenal carcinomas"
]
},
" "
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"7b6da4",
"children":[
"Clinical findings highly specific for Cushing syndrome include:"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"99f257",
"children":[
"proximal muscle weakness"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"404fe0",
"children":[
"facial plethora"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"a25aec",
"children":[
"supraclavicular or dorsocervical (“buffalo hump”) fat pads"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"fdab36",
"children":[
"wide (>1 cm) violaceous striae"
]
},
" "
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_en_s13_2",
"title":{
"__html":"Testing"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"fa6a5a",
"children":[
"Testing"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"c7cc46",
"children":[
"First-line diagnostic studies include:"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"35cb06",
"children":[
"1-mg overnight dexamethasone suppression test (failure to suppress serum cortisol to <3 μg/dL)"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"009326",
"children":[
"24-hour urine cortisol level (elevated)"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"00d813",
"children":[
"late night salivary cortisol level (elevated)"
]
},
" "
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"2dd24b",
"children":[
"If the cortisol level is elevated (or not suppressible), obtain an ACTH level to differentiate ACTH-dependent from ACTH-independent hypercortisolism."
]
},
{
"type":"inline-wrap",
"wrapId":"1",
"contentIds":[
"mk19_bb_en_s13_inline_t1"
],
"forceOpen":true
},
{
"type":"heading",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
"Don't Be Tricked"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"a23f82",
"children":[
"Evaluation for Cushing syndrome should be limited to patients with a significant clinical suspicion of disease, including specific signs of Cushing syndrome or an adrenal mass."
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"098739",
"children":[
"False-positive results (failure to suppress cortisol) with the 1-mg dexamethasone suppression test are common owing to alcohol use, obesity, and psychological disorders."
]
},
" "
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_en_s13_3",
"title":{
"__html":"Treatment"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"4c4ac0",
"children":[
"Treatment"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"edcb51",
"children":[
"Surgical resection is the definitive treatment for benign and malignant cortisol-secreting adrenal tumors. Bisphosphonates are the treatment of choice for low bone density caused by hypercortisolism."
]
},
{
"type":"inline-wrap",
"wrapId":"2",
"contentIds":[
"mk19_bb_en_f06"
],
"forceOpen":true
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_en_s13_4",
"title":{
"__html":"Test Yourself"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"7866cc",
"children":[
"Test Yourself"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"85c94a",
"class":"test",
"children":[
"A 43-year-old woman has diabetes mellitus; hypertension; hirsutism; and wide, purple abdominal striae. The serum cortisol level is 26 μg/dL after administration of 1 mg of dexamethasone. The serum ACTH level is 50 pg/mL."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"124f5d",
"class":"test_answer",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Answer:"
]
},
" ",
"For diagnosis, choose pituitary tumor. For testing, select pituitary gland MRI."
]
}
]
}
]
},
